{
  "title": "Designing Command Line Interface (CLI) Tools Using FastAPI with Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide explains how to leverage FastAPI, a modern, fast (high-performance), web framework for building APIs, to create powerful command-line interface (CLI) tools in Python 3.12+.",

  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI is not limited to web services; it can also be used for creating CLI tools.",
    "CLI tools provide a user-friendly interface to interact with applications without a graphical user interface (GUI).",
    "Incorporating FastAPI offers benefits such as type checking, improved API documentation, and automatic validation.",
    "FastAPI's flexible routing system supports both web requests and command line arguments."
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "Python",
      "code": """
from fastapi import FastAPI, Argument, FastAPIResponse

app = FastAPI()

@app.get("/{command}")
def run(command: str):
    if command == 'example':
        return {"result": "This is an example response from the CLI tool."}
    else:
        return FastAPIResponse(status_code=404)
      """
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "Python 3.12+ is required to run this code.",
    "FastAPI version 0.73.0 or higher is needed for CLI functionality."
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "When creating a CLI tool, you may need to handle additional command line arguments such as flags and subcommands.",
    "To run the FastAPI application as a standalone CLI, use the uvicorn or fastapi-cli command-line tools."
  ]
}
